const faqs = [
  {
    q: "Why does WhisperKool repair require EPA 608 certified technicians?",
    a: "Federal law (Clean Air Act Section 608) requires EPA certification for any technician who opens a refrigerant circuit. WhisperKool units run R-134a, R-410a, or R-513A depending on the series. EPA fines for unlicensed refrigerant work run up to $44,539 per violation under current penalty schedules, and uncertified techs typically don't have the recovery and evacuation equipment that the law requires anyway. Our techs hold EPA 608 Universal certification (#1346255700410) — the highest cert tier, covering small appliance, low-pressure, and high-pressure refrigerant work. The cert is verifiable through the EPA's database directly."
  },
  {
    q: "What's the difference between WhisperKool repair and regular HVAC service?",
    a: "Two layers of difference — licensing and discipline. On licensing: California regulates appliance repair under BHGS (Bureau of Household Goods and Services), separately from HVAC contracting under CSLB. WhisperKool service falls under appliance-repair scope, not HVAC. We hold BHGS Registration #A49573 specifically for appliance work. On discipline: standard HVAC techs are trained for 35-40°F refrigeration or 68-78°F space-cooling load, not 55°F at 60-70% relative humidity. Wine cellar cooling has its own load calculation, its own humidity management, and its own failure patterns. We've seen techs treat wine cellars like big refrigerators — the result is temperature swings and condensate problems."
  },
  {
    q: "How fast can you respond to a WhisperKool service call?",
