<!-- 01 INTRO + CROSS-LINK TO PILLAR -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">01, About this service</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">When your WhisperKool stops cooling, repair speed and the right credentials matter more than typical appliance work.</h2>

    <p>WhisperKool builds the most-installed premium wine cellar cooling brand across LA — SC Pro Series flagships, Platinum Split estate units, Slimline and Ceiling Mount mid-tiers, plus a long tail of legacy XLT and original SC Series units still running in cellars built between 2008 and 2019. For full brand background, the complete model lineup, and model-specific failure patterns, see our <a href="/brands/whisperkool/">WhisperKool brand page</a>.</p>

    <p>This page is about what happens when yours stops working — and why getting WhisperKool repair right matters more than typical appliance work. <strong>Wine cellar cooling failure costs more than cooling failure anywhere else.</strong> A refrigerator warming up costs you groceries. A wine cellar warming up costs you a 1,200-bottle collection that took 15 years to build. Speed of response and depth of expertise both matter, and the regulatory layer underneath both matters more than most homeowners realize.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 02 REGULATORY DIFFERENTIATION -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">02, Why this isn't standard HVAC work</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">WhisperKool repair requires more than a generic HVAC license.</h2>

    <p class="lead">Three regulatory and technical realities separate WhisperKool service from everyday cooling repair. Knowing them protects you from hiring the wrong technician for the job.</p>

    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li><strong>EPA 608 Universal certification is federally required for any refrigerant work.</strong> WhisperKool units run R-134a, R-410a, or R-513A depending on the series. The Clean Air Act Section 608 requires EPA certification for any technician who opens the refrigerant circuit, recovers refrigerant, or recharges. Universal cert (the highest tier) covers small appliance, low-pressure, and high-pressure systems — which is what cellar-cooling work actually requires. Penalties for unlicensed refrigerant work run up to $44,539 per violation. Our techs hold cert #1346255700410, verifiable through the EPA database.</li>
      <li><strong>BHGS appliance registration is the right California license for the work — not CSLB HVAC.</strong> California regulates appliance repair under the Bureau of Household Goods and Services, separately from HVAC contracting under the Contractors State License Board. WhisperKool service falls under appliance-repair scope. Our BHGS Registration is #A49573. Hiring an HVAC contractor for WhisperKool work often means working without the correct California licensing for the task.</li>
      <li><strong>Wine cellar conditions aren't refrigerator conditions.</strong> A cellar holds 55°F at 60-70% relative humidity — not 35-40°F like a fridge, not 68-78°F like a space-cooled room. Standard refrigeration techs are trained on different load calculations and different humidity management. We've seen techs treat wine cellars like oversized refrigerators, with the predictable results: temperature swings, mold growth on cabinetry, condensate pooling. Cellar cooling is its own discipline, and it's the discipline our team is trained for.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 03 SERVICE WORKFLOW -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">03, How our service call works</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">A WhisperKool repair, start to finish.</h2>

    <p class="lead">Four steps from the call to the closed ticket. The process is the same whether your unit is an SC Pro Series or a 12-year-old XLT.</p>

    <div class="step-grid">
      <div class="step-card">
        <h3>Step 1 — Diagnostic visit ($89)</h3>
        <p>Tech arrives same-day if booked before 2pm. Visual inspection of condenser, lineset (split systems), controller display, condensate drain. Pressure test on the refrigerant circuit if the symptoms point that direction. Heat-load calculation if cellar temps are consistently off — sometimes the problem is cellar insulation rather than the cooling unit. You receive a written diagnostic and a written quote before any work proceeds.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="step-card">
        <h3>Step 2 — Quote and approval</h3>
        <p>We separately itemize parts, labor, and refrigerant if needed. Diagnostic fee is waived when you approve the repair. Sometimes the diagnostic concludes that replacement makes more economic sense than repair — for old XLT compressor failures, original Extreme Series at end of life. We show the numbers both ways and explain the reasoning. Your decision, not ours.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="step-card">
        <h3>Step 3 — Same-day repair when parts on truck</h3>
        <p>We carry common WhisperKool parts on the van: ICU control boards, PDT thermostats for legacy XLT, drain pump motors, condenser fan motors, run capacitors, both R-134a and R-410a refrigerant. Less common parts — specific compressor models, proprietary OEM components — order direct from WhisperKool's Pulaski, Tennessee facility with 1-3 business day lead time. You'll know during diagnostic whether the repair completes same-day or needs a return visit.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="step-card">
        <h3>Step 4 — Final test and documentation</h3>
        <p>24-48 hour temperature stability test — the cellar should hold setpoint within ±1°F after a successful repair. We provide a written service report covering parts used, work performed, refrigerant recovery and recharge amounts (required by EPA recordkeeping), and photographs of the unit before and after. The report is yours for warranty claims, future service, or insurance documentation.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 04 COMMON SCENARIOS (BRIEF — pillar covers depth) -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">04, Common service scenarios</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What we see most often on WhisperKool calls.</h2>

    <p class="lead">Brief overview here — for series-by-series detail and year-pattern observations, see the <a href="/brands/whisperkool/">WhisperKool brand page</a>.</p>

    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li><strong>Cellar climbing past 60°F (about 40% of our calls):</strong> Almost always condenser-coil dust accumulation. Cleaning plus airflow check, no parts. $185-$250 service call. We don't oversell.</li>
      <li><strong>Refrigerant leak (split systems):</strong> Pinhole leaks in indoor evaporator coil or lineset connections. EPA 608 work — pressure test, leak isolation, repair, recharge. Typical $400-$650 total.</li>
      <li><strong>ICU / PDT controller failure:</strong> SC Pro shows alarm code; XLT thermostat fails entirely. Replacement $280-$450 depending on series. XLT chassis can also be retrofit with a modern digital controller for another 3-5 years of service.</li>
      <li><strong>Condensate drain issues:</strong> Water backing up into the cellar or pooling near the unit. Urgent — wine cellar humidity plus standing water creates mold conditions on cabinetry quickly. Drain line clearing or condensate evaporator/pump replacement.</li>
      <li><strong>Compressor end-of-life (year 10-15 typical):</strong> Honest framing — if your XLT is 12+ years old and the compressor failed, replacement WhisperKool runs $1,800-$3,500 installed depending on series, and a comprehensive XLT compressor rebuild can hit $1,200+ in parts alone. We quote both paths and let you decide.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>

